<div class=Section1>

<h3><a name=addinfo><u>Additional Information:</u></a><o:p></o:p></h3>

<p>The purpose of this Working Group (WG) is to aid in the provision of
interoperability between current and future batch systems on a Grid. This will
be done by providing a specification for an abstract standard Job Submission
Description Language (JSDL) for describing computational batch jobs and their
required execution environments. A normative XML Schema of the JSDL
specification will also be provided, in order to aid the uptake of the
language. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p>Batch jobs described using the JSDL, can be submitted to a computational
Grid of heterogeneous batch systems that can translate to and from this
abstract standard language. In this scheme, a User or Client (application)
submitting a computational batch job to a computational Grid via a batch
system, would construct a document complying with the JSDL schema. This
document would encapsulate all of the information that is needed by a batch
system (Distributed Resource Management (DRM) system), or a batch job
submission system on a Grid, which may be accessible through an end-user client
application or portal, or a Grid Meta-Scheduler, to place a computational batch
job in its required environment for execution via one of a number of local
(conventional) batch systems that can understand the JSDL schema. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p>An end-user need not write the JSDL document for their job directly.
Instead, they may take advantage of translators that would compose a JSDL
document from a description that the user has supplied in a native language,
such as Condor's <span class=SpellE>ClassAds</span>, if such a translator was
available. Thus, an end-user need not learn yet another language, and can
continue to use their <span class=SpellE>favourite</span> language and end-user
interface. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p>In addition to the computational requirements of batch jobs, such as
physical memory or architecture, the JSDL must describe other information such
as the locations of the input and output files that are required for the
execution of a batch job. Techniques for the transfer of input and output files
and data may also be described using the JSDL. The JSDL should also provide a
means to enable the description of basic dependencies between jobs, that is,
the dependency of a job on the status of other jobs, and any relationships
between the input and output files of jobs. We do not concern ourselves with
job scheduling and the selection of resources on a Grid, leaving this to other efforts
within the <a href="http://www-unix.mcs.anl.gov/~schopf/ggf-sched/">Scheduling
Area</a> of the <a href="http://www.gridforum.org/">Global Grid Forum (GGF)</a>.
<o:p></o:p></p>

<p>It is clear that in addition to a JSDL, there is a need for a standard
abstract Resource Description Language (RDL) in order for Grid Meta-Schedulers
to be able to match job requirements to resource capabilities. This will then
enable these schedulers to undertake advanced reservation, job scheduling, and
subsequent submission of Grid batch jobs to batch systems on Grids and the
resources that they administer. Although it is out-with the scope of the work
of this WG to address the issues of an RDL, there is a need to provide the
semantics for a minimum set of RDL attributes in order that resource
requirements may be addressed in the JSDL. It is envisaged that the need for an
RDL will be addressed by a sister group within GGF, possibly building on the
work of the <a href="http://www.dmtf.org/standards/standard_cim.php">Common
Information Model (CIM)</a> group, which will provide a specification of that
language. <o:p></o:p></p>

<h4><u>Scope</u><o:p></o:p></h4>

<p>A number of languages currently exist for submitting computational jobs to
resources, potentially through a batch system. These include the <a
href="http://eu-datagrid.web.cern.ch/eu-datagrid/">EU-<span class=SpellE>DataGrid</span></a><span
class=SpellE>'s</span> Job Description Language (JDL), <a
href="http://www.cs.wisc.edu/condor/">Condor</a>'s <span class=SpellE>ClassAds</span>,
and <a href="http://www.globus.org/"><span class=SpellE>Globus</span></a><span
class=SpellE>'s</span> Resource Specification Language (RSL). While these
languages are not explicitly XML based, many are beginning to provide
incompatible XML equivalents that are inhibiting interoperability. We are
deliberately focusing our work on the definition and delivery of an abstract
standard language (the JSDL), and a normative XML Schema of this language, to
ensure compatibility within a computational Grid environment based on, though
not limited to, the emerging <a href="http://www.ggf.org/ogsa-wg/">Open Grid
Services Architecture (OGSA)</a>. The intention of this WG is to develop a
specification for a JSDL that encompasses the common functionalities of a
number of widely used batch systems. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p>The JSDL specification would be used for describing the requirements of
computational jobs in order for them to be submitted between computational Grid
entities at the user or agent/client application level, and the scheduling
layers, as depicted in the figure below. A batch job execution service such as
a DRM system, or a scheduling service such as a Grid Meta-Scheduler, may accept
such a JSDL document and submit the job to a batch system that can understand
the JSDL schema, through an API such as that defined by the <a
href="http://www.drmaa.org/">Distributed Resource Management Application API
(DRMAA)</a> Working Group. The JSDL would make use of the work undertaken
within the <a href="http://www.fz-juelich.de/zam/RD/coop/ggf/sd-wg.html">Scheduling
Dictionary Working Group</a> of the <span class=SpellE>GGF's</span> Scheduling
Area, to define the semantics and syntax for the JSDL specification and its
normative XML Schema. The Scheduling Dictionary Working Group's goal is stated
as, <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><i>&quot;The
objective of this Working Group is to support and enhance <br>
interoperability between different scheduling systems by providing a <br>
summary of terminology encountered with various schedulers. <b>This <br>
information could then be used to develop a grid language that would <br>
provide seamless communication and advanced reservation capabilities to <br>
the various schedulers in use</b>.&quot; </i><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p>It is clear that the requirements of the <i>&quot;grid language&quot;</i>
referred to above, can in part be fulfilled by the JSDL. The JSDL would use the
&quot;scheduling terminology encountered with various schedulers&quot; as <span
class=SpellE>summarised</span> by the Dictionary Working Group. The RDL
introduced above should also make use of the work undertaken within the
Dictionary Working Group. This is important for compatible semantics between
the RDL and JSDL, when describing job requirement attributes and resource
attributes for job submission and scheduling needs, particularly for use by
high level Grid Meta-Schedulers. <o:p></o:p></p>

